               <p>JAMES KEVILL. I live in <placeName id="t18310217-229-crimeloc1345">Lucas-street</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18310217-229-crimeloc1345" type="placeName" value="Lucas-street"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18310217-229-crimeloc1345" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18310217-229-off1343 t18310217-229-crimeloc1345"></join>; the <rs id="t18310217-229-deflabel1346" type="occupation">prisoner was servant to Captain Pearson</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18310217-229-defend2144 t18310217-229-deflabel1346"></join>, and lived in the same house. I saw a waistcoat at the Police-office, which was mine; I had not missed it - it had been in a trunk in my room.</p>

               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310217-229-person2147">
                  DAVID 
                  MOSES
               <interp inst="t18310217-229-person2147" type="surname" value="MOSES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310217-229-person2147" type="given" value="DAVID"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310217-229-person2147" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am in the employ of my brother, who keeps a slopseller's shop, in High-street, Shadwell. On the 16th of February the prisoner came, and brought a waistcoat in his hat, which he asked me to buy - I asked whose it was? he said his own - he asked 2s. for it, and I gave him 1s. 6d.; I gave the same waistcoat to the prosecutor.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310217-229-person2148">
                  HENRY 
                  LEE
               <interp inst="t18310217-229-person2148" type="surname" value="LEE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310217-229-person2148" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310217-229-person2148" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a Police-constable. On the 16th of February I took the prisoner, in the Back-road, St, George's in the East - I said, "Don't you live at Mr. Pearson's?" he said Yes - I said, you must go with me; he said he had taken the waistcoat.(Property produced and sworn to.)</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I lived with Captain 
               <persName id="t18310217-229-person2149">Pearson</persName>
             some months - I was sick, and I took the waistcoat to get some medicine from the hospital; I came from Spanish-town, Jamaica.</p>
               <p>GUILTY. Aged 17.</p>
